text: Structure and Biosynthesis of Isatropolones, Bioactive Amine- Scavenging Fluorescent Natural Products from Streptomyces Gç66 Xiaofeng Cai+, Yi-Ming Shi+, Nicole Pçhlmann, Ole Revermann, Isabel Bahner, Sacha J. Pidot, Frank Wesche, Helmut Lackner, Claudia B(cid:2)chel, Marcel Kaiser, Christian Richter, Harald Schwalbe, Timothy P. Stinear, Axel Zeeck, and Helge B. Bode* Abstract: The natural products isatropolone A–C (1–3) were reisolated from Streptomyces Gç66, with 1 and 3 showing potent activity against Leishmania donovani. They contain a rare tropolone ring derived from a type II polyketide biosynthesis pathway. Their biosynthesis was elucidated by labeling experiments, analysis of the biosynthesis gene cluster, its partial heterologous expression, and structural character- ization of various intermediates. Owing to their 1,5-diketone moiety, they can react with ammonia, amines, lysine, and lysine-containing peptides and proteins, which results in the formation of a covalent bond and subsequent pyridine ring formation. Their fluorescence properties change upon amine binding, enabling the simple visualization of reacted amines including proteins. Electrophilic natural products with Michael acceptors, ring-

strained scaffolds such as epoxides, lactones, or lactams, or other moieties often show a biological activity that is the result of their intrinsic reactivity with cellular nucleophiles such as cysteine, serine, threonine, or lysine residues.[1, 2] Despite the success of such compounds since the early days of natural product research, with b-lactams as one of the most widely used class of antibiotics, for example, such compounds have been almost neglected in the last years as their high reactivity is often assumed to result in low selectivity. Fortunately, this view is currently changing because several compounds show selectivity despite an electrophilic moiety,[3] and several synthetic electrophiles have been successfully brought to the clinic or are currently in clinical trials.[4–6] Furthermore, their reactivity often enables the identification of their molecular target using modern chemical biology and Angew. There are also natural products that are so reactive that they react already in the producing organisms or the growth medium. Examples are the fungal azaphilones,[8] which can react with different amines, amino acids, or even peptides,[9] resulting in the production of pigments or even potent inhibitors of protein–protein interactions. Similar compounds from bacteria are the rubrolones,[10, 11] which are tropolone- and pyridine-containing natural products from Streptomyces. Very recently, their biosynthesis has been investigated,[11] and it has been shown that while the tropolone ring results from rearrangement of an intermediate of a type II polyketide synthase (PKS) pathway, the pyridine ring is formed non- enzymatically between an amine and the 1,5-diketone moiety present in the rubrolone precursor.[12] However, the free amine precursor was only identified after manipulation of the biosynthesis gene cluster (BGC), resulting in the production of the putative aglycone. Herein, we describe the identification and biosynthesis of isatropolones A–C (1–3),[13] natural products from Strepto- myces Gç66 that still contain a 1,5-diketone moiety, which can efficiently form a pyridine ring with different amines includ- ing lysine residues from proteins, in addition to an unusual tropolone ring. Upon pyridine formation, the fluorescence properties of the isatropolone change, enabling the simple visualization of the newly formed isarubrolone derivatives. Chemical screening of Streptomyces Gç66 revealed the presence of three yellowish-red pigments 1–3, which were produced in yields of 12, 6, and 3 mg L(cid:2)1 in shaking flasks and in yields of up to 50 mg L(cid:2)1 in an airlift fermenter (see the

Supporting Information, Figure S1).[13] Compounds 1 and 2 have the same sum formula of C24H24O9, which was deter- mined by HR-ESI/MS, while compound 3 contains one additional oxygen atom (Table S1). Details on the isolation and structure elucidation of 1–3 are only mentioned briefly here as they have already been described in a PhD thesis.[13] Analysis of the NMR data (1H, 13C, COSY, HSQC, HMBC, and ROESY; Figures S2 and S3) of the main product 1 ena- bled the determination of its structure. Whereas a methyl group, a butyryl moiety, and 6-deoxy-d-allosylpyranoside as a sugar moiety connected to a dihydrofuran could be readily (Fig- identified ure S2), the assignment of the remaining molecule was complicated by the presence sp2 of carbon atoms among the remaining ten carbon atoms (Table S2). 3 carried the same sugar as 1 but a hydroxylated butyryl moiety (Figure S3 and Tables S3 and S4). However, based on subsequent HMBC experiments, an unusual tropolone struc- ture similar to that found in rubrolones A (4) and B (5) was suggested[11] (Figure S2) for 1–3 although 4 and 5 contain an extra pyridine ring and a different sugar moiety. As the rubrolones have been shown to be derived from an isatropo- lone-like precursor identified after deletion of the predicted glycosyltransferase,[12] 1–3 were incubated with ammonia, which led to clean conversion into the corresponding pyridine derivatives named isarubrolones A–C (6–8). Detailed NMR analysis of 6–8 (Tables S5–S7) as well as of acetate-labeled 1 after a subsequent reaction with ammonia (Table S5 and Figure 1 b) using also an INADEQUATE experiment con- firmed all structures. Bioactivity tests with 1–3 and 6–9 did not reveal any antimicrobial activity, and only very weak cytotoxic activity was observed (Table 1), similar to the low cytotoxic and antioxidative activities described for 4.[11] However, when these compounds were tested against different protozoa (Trypanosoma, Plasmodium, and Leishmania; Table S8), very promising activity of 1 against Leishmania donovani, the causative agent of visceral leishmaniasis, was observed Angew. (IC50 = 0.5 mm), which was comparable to that of the positive control miltefosine (IC50 = 0.3 mm ; Table 1). Whereas the activity of 3 was four times weaker than that of 1, all other compounds were even less potent, pointing to a specific target of 1 in L. donovani that requires the 3’-R found in 1 and 3 as well as the 1,5-diketone moiety. Unfortunately, no activity against Leishmania-infected macrophages could be detected, indicating that the isatropolones do not reach the intracellular pathogen.

As the structures of the isatropolones suggested a biosyn- thetic pathway related to that of the rubrolones, the genome of the Gç66 strain was sequenced to compare the rubrolone- and isatropolone-producing BGCs. Antismash analysis[14] of the Gç66 genome sequence led to the identification of two BGCs encoding type II PKSs. One of them encoded an additional ketosynthase III, which was assumed to be involved in the biosynthesis of the butyryl starter unit as described for the biosynthesis of R1128,[15] alnumycin,[16] and rubrolone[12] to which the genes have the highest similarity (Figures 1 and S4 a and Table S9). Heterologous expression of istG-R in S. lividans (Figure S5) resulted in a strongly red pigmented phenotype as also observed for Gç66 (Figure S6). HPLC/MS analysis of extracted agar plates revealed the presence of compounds 9 and 10 (Figure S7 and Table S1). Structure elucidation of 9 revealed the presence of a reduced tropolone derivative as a mixture of two diastereomers (Table S10 and Figure 2). Additionally, the expected oxidized aglycone 10 was determined by its MS and UV data (Fig- ure S7) and compared with the literature data.[12] Both findings confirm the involvement of the ist BGC in isatropo- lone biosynthesis, which should thus be very similar to the proposed rubrolone biosynthesis pathway (Figure S8). The rearrangement during tropolone ring formation is supported not only by the occurrence of the required genes in the gene cluster (Table S9) but also by in-depth labeling experiments showing a 2JCC coupling between C11 and C12 after feeding of [1,2-13C2]acetate (Figure 1 and Tables S2–S4).

Interestingly, the ist BGC is different to the recently described rub BCG[12] as no sugar biosynthesis genes and no acyl carrier protein (ACP) are involved in the starter unit biosynthesis (Figure S4 a). However, sugar biosynthesis genes resembling those of rubrolone biosynthesis have been found in the genome at a distance of 290 kb. Nevertheless, the Angew. Chem. Int. See Table S10 for more data. production of 9 and 10 from the expression of istG-R in S. lividans revealed that the ACP might come from the S. lividans fatty acid biosynthesis pathway because no suitable sugar is available for glycosylation in S. lividans, thus leading to the production of the aglycone only (Figure S4 b). While it was not clear which of the three oxygenases are involved in tropolone ring formation during rubrolone biosynthesis,[12] production of the tropolone derivatives 9 and 10 after expression of istG-R indicates that IstP (= RubB) seems to be the only oxygenase required for this rearrangement. Additionally, the dehydrogenase IstL, the reductase IstO, and the dehydratase IstQ might also be involved.

Aside from the unusual tropolone biosynthesis, which is a novel variation of the well-known type II PKS biosynthesis pathway, the ability of the isatropolones to bind amines in a covalent fashion is another unusual feature. Several differ- ent amines showed reactivity with 1 but especially lysine showed very efficient conversion (Figures 3 a and S8 and Table S11), which was also observed for aglycone 10 (Fig- ure S9). Not surprisingly, the UV (Figure S10 a) and fluores- cence spectra (Figures 3 b and S10 b) of 1 and 6 are quite different, enabling the simple identification of isarubrolones even when bound to proteins and thus the labeling of lysine- containing proteins as exemplified for bovine serum albumin (BSA; Figures 3 b and S11). Reactions of various lysine- containing peptides (Figures 4 a and S12 a) with 1 followed by MS analysis gave the expected mass shift for these peptides of 438 Da, which results from the isarubrolone modification (Figures 4 b and S12 b). The reactivity of the 1,5-diketone-containing isatropo- lones towards amines, including lysine residues of proteins, might be the reason for their promising biological activity against L. donovani. Although 1 showed no activity against intracellular Leishmania, it would be interesting to elucidate its molecular target in this pathogen as this might allow the future development of anti-Leishmania drugs. As 1 is avail- able from two companies,[17] such research is also open to groups with no access to Streptomyces cultivation and natural product isolation. Moreover, the unusual fluorescence prop- erties of the isatropolones might motivate the development of similar or simplified 1,5-diketones as probes for the covalent labeling and visualization of amine-containing molecules, including peptides and proteins, similar to commercially available dyes (e.g., Cy dyes).
